FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - MIDDLE EAST (07): LIBYA, SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 13 Nov 2012
Source: Libya Herald via Flutrackers [summarised, edited]
http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?t=194966


Reports have emerged from the southern town of Kufra that a possible outbreak of foot and mouth disease (FMD) has begun to infect livestock there. Suspicions were raised following the deaths of 5 cows on one of the farms, with at least 2 livestock barns feared to have been infected in the town. Tests have yet to confirm the presence of the disease, but [samples] have been flown to Benghazi for analysis.

It is believed that the disease is likely to have been brought to Kufra by imported livestock, much of which comes from nearby Sudan, which has suffered numerous outbreaks of FMD in recent years. Egypt is also suffering from a serious FMD outbreak, with an estimated 6.3 million buffalo and cattle and 7.5 million sheep and goats at risk, according to the UN's Food & Agriculture Organisation.

Libya officially confirmed an outbreak of the SAT2 strain of FMD back in February this year [2012], with the last reported outbreak back in 2003. That outbreak, which was identified in an area south east of Benghazi, was of particular concern because the required vaccination is not widely used in Libya.

Two separate strains continue to circulate at several locations along the coast in the east and west of the country, with the government response including vaccination campaigns, movement controls, and closing of livestock markets where necessary.

Source: Libya Herald http://www.libyaherald.com/2012/11/13/possible-foot-and-mouth-outbreak-reported-in-kufra/.

[byline: George Grant]

